The '''quantum concentration''' {{math|''n''<sub>Q</sub>}} is the [[particle density (particle count)|particle concentration]] (i.e. the number of particles per unit volume) of a system where the [[mean inter-particle distance|interparticle distance]] is equal to the [[thermal de Broglie wavelength]].

Quantum effects become appreciable when the particle concentration is greater than or equal to the quantum concentration, which is defined as:<ref name="Kittel">{{cite book|title= Thermal Physics|edition=2|publisher=W. H. Freeman|year=1980|pages=73–77|author=[[Charles Kittel]]|author2=[[Herbert Kroemer]]|isbn=978-0716710882}}</ref>
:<math>n_{\rm Q}=\left(\frac{M k T}{2 \pi \hbar^2}\right)^{3/2}</math>
:where:
:{{mvar|M}} is the mass of the particles in the system
:{{mvar|k}} is the [[Boltzmann constant]]
:{{mvar|T}} is the temperature as measured in [[kelvin]]s
:<math>\hbar</math> is the [[Planck constant|reduced Planck constant]]

The quantum concentration for room temperature protons is about 1/cubic-Angstrom.

As the quantum concentration depends on temperature, high temperatures will put most systems in the classical limit unless they have a very high density e.g. a [[White dwarf]].

For an ideal gas the [[Sackur–Tetrode equation]] can be written in terms of the quantum concentration as<ref name="Kittel"/>
:<math>S(T,V,N)=N k_{\rm B}\left[\frac{5}{2}+\ln\left(\frac{n_{\rm Q}}{n}\right)\right]</math>

